The article discusses the life and achievements of Madeleine Albright, highlighting her defiance of convention and the barriers she broke throughout her career. Albright was an immigrant and refugee who became a proud American. She worked tirelessly to raise her three daughters while pursuing a doctorate degree and a career in American diplomacy. She held positions in the Senate, the National Security Council, and ultimately became the first woman Secretary of State under President Clinton. Albright was a scholar, teacher, bestselling author, and successful businesswoman who believed in America's importance on the global stage. She inspired countless women leaders around the world and was known for her goodness, grace, and commitment to freedom. The article concludes by stating that in recognition of Albright's service to the nation, President Biden has ordered the flag of the United States to be flown at half-staff in her honor.